      <div xml:id="NA156-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu (ET: tōḻi) iravukkuṟi maṟuttatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how a night tryst is refused.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA156">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nīyē</l>
<l>            yaṭiyaṟin totuṅkā vāriruḷ vanteṅ</l>
<l>            kaṭiyuṭai viyaṉakark kāva ṉīviyum</l>
<l>            pēraṉ piṉaiyō peruṅka ṉāṭa</l>
<l>            yāmē</l>
<l>            niṉṉuniṉ malaiyum pāṭip paṉṉāṭ</l>
<l>            ciṟutiṉai kākkuvañ cēṟu mataṉāṟ </l>
<l>            pakalvan tīmō palpaṭa rakala</l>
<l>            veruvai nīṭiya peruvaraic ciṟukuṭi</l>
<l>            yariya lārntava rāyiṉum periyar</l>
<l>            pāṭimiḻ viṭarmukai muḻaṅka</l>
<l>            vāṭumaḻai yiṟuttateṅ kōṭuyar kuṉṟē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>You have great love, o man from the land of big stones,</l>
<l rend="indent">you, coming through difficult darkness, when [orientation] is reduced to</l>
<l rend="indent">knowing by foot, and passing by the watch of our well-protected wide mansion.</l>
<l rend="indent">We, singing you and your mountain for many days,</l>
<l>we go and guard the small millet.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Therefore</l>
<l>please come at midday.</l>
<l rend="indent3">For many afflictions to depart</l>
<l>the playing rain tarried on our high-peaked hills</l>
<l rend="indent">so that it thunders in clefts [and] caves that are humming from the singing</l>
<l rend="indent2">of [our?] great people, even if they have become full of toddy in</l>
<l rend="indent2">the small hamlet on the big mountain where the reeds have grown long.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="6b">
    <l>please come at midday, for many afflictions to depart.<note place="foot">T.V.G. includes this part into the imperative sentences.</note></l>
</lg>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="8b">
    <l>[Our] people have great [wrath] even if they are full of toddy.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="9f.b">
<l>Playing rain tarried on our high-peaked hill</l>
<l>so that it roars in clefts [and] caves, humming from thunder.<note place="foot">Thus the way T.V.G. understands the syntax. I feel this is rather weak with a <term xml:lang="ta">periyar</term> neither specified (as to wrath) nor marked as a predicate noun.</note></l>
    </lg>
        </lg>
